  "slug": "poulet-a-la-moutarde",
  "title": "Poulet à la Moutarde",
  "subtitle": "French chicken with Dijon and cream",
  "excerpt": "Chicken thighs browned in butter, deglazed with white wine, and finished in a sauce of Dijon mustard and double cream. Sharp, rich, and quick enough for a weeknight.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Poulet à la moutarde is a classic French bistro dish, particularly associated with Burgundy and Dijon. Documented in Julia Child, Louisette Bertholle, and Simone Beck, Mastering the Art of French Cooking (1961) and Elizabeth David, French Provincial Cooking (1960).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The key to this dish is when the mustard goes in. Add it to the pan while the heat is on and it turns bitter; stir it into the cream before the cream goes in and it disperses evenly; this is the correct method. The mustard provides sharpness, the cream provides richness, and the two balance each other.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Use bone-in, skin-on thighs: they have better flavour than breasts and don't dry out during the braise. The skin, browned at the start, makes the pan sauce significantly better.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
